<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/9932> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #9932" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/23> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "pp. 65-72" .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/9127> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #9127" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/7> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/2> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "p. 755, footnote 473" .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/7310> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #7310" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/5> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "Procos. in Africa. As noted in MRR 2.222, his command in Africa in 51 indicates that he had been praetor by or before 54. It seems possible that he was a praetor then, governed Africa from 53 to 50 in succession to P. Attius Varus, and returned in 50 in time to be a candidate for the consulship of 49 (Schol. Gron. 291St; see Sumner, Phoenix 25, 1971, 268, note 41), leaving Q. Ligarius, his legatus, in command.\n" .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/7298> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #7298" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/5> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "See MRR 2.237, Quaesitores, and 240, note 3. According to Mommsen (StR 2?.584) the presiding officer of a quaestio de vi was never a magistrate in office (see also J. Linderski, HSPh 76, 1972, 195-198, note 59). Considius, the quaesitor in 52, may be either M. Considius Longus (11), procos. in Africa 51-50, or M. Considius Nonianus, who was allotted the succession to Caesar in Cisalpine Gaul in 49 (MRR 2.242, 250, 261).\n" .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/5831> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #5831" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/2> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "Legatus pro praetore under Metellus Scipio in Africa (CIL 12.2.780ILS 5319). He held command of the garrison at Hadrumetum (Bell. Afr. 3-5; 33; 43), besieged Achulla (43), and garrisoned Thysdrus (76, and 86), and was finally killed by his own troops (93)." .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/5760> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #5760" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/2> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "Legatus pro praetore under Metellus Scipio in Africa (CIL 12.2.780–ILS 5319; cf. Bell. Afr. 4)." .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/5695> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #5695" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/2> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "Probably continued as a Legatus pro praetore with Attius Varus in Africa (see 49, and 47, Legates)." .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/5580> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #5580" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/2> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "Served in Africa, probably like Attius Varus, who was a Legatus pro praetore (Caes. BC 2.23.4; cf. CIL 12.2.780-ILS 5319, Leg. pro pr.)." .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/5456> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #5456" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/2> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "Returned from Africa late in 50 to canvass for the consulship (Cic. Lig. 2; Schol. Gron. 291 Stangl; see 51, Promagistrates)." .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/5393> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #5393" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/2> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "Governor of Africa in 50 and probably in 51 (see 50, Promagistrates)." .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/5341> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #5341" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/2> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "Presided over the trial of Saufeius under the Lex Plautia de vi (Ascon. 55 C)." .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/5039> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #5039" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/2> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "Cic. Lig. 2; Schol. Gron. 291 Stangl. See 50, Promagistrates." .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/5038> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #5038" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/2> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "The following men held provincial governorships immediately after the passage in 52 of the Pompeian law which established an interval between the praetorship or consulship and a provincial command, and may therefore have held the praetorship before 57 (all the Praetors of 57 are known). It is however more probable that the law did not apply to magistrates in office in 53 and 52 (see 54, Praetors), hence these dates remain only as possibilities." .
